Not that I necessarily agree that this is the only reason for sluggish buffing, but if you give it some thought, it certainly doesn't seem all that hard to believe.  For every one player-made pet, how many NPC pets with buffs (and NPCs with buffs, for that matter) do you think exist in the game world?  The servers have to manage those, too.<br>
<br>
The entire act of checking every single NPC and NPC/PC pet that is alive at time X, what buffs they have, what buffs they're missing, what class they are (and thus what buffs they have access to cast), and whether they should refresh any buffs probably is rather resource intensive.  If they made this check every second of every minute... well, you can probably see how resources can start to add up.  Logically, you space these checks out to balance the load.<br>
<br>
I think that as much as we'd like to believe that there isn't any limit to what can be done within EQ, the reality is that there are still some technical restrictions that stand in the way (even if they do seem rather minor <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) <p><font face="Verdana">
<b><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=24658" target=_blank>Sambus Veneficus</a></b><br> Arch Mage of Ak'anon<br> Mithaniel Marr Server</font><br><br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=rhasinfirestorm>Rhasin Firestorm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sage</span><br>  Posts: 966<br> <font color=#333333>(7/16/02 4:44:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=571.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_mad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Pet Complaints!!! &gt;:-\</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Not that I necessarily agree that this is the only reason for sluggish buffing, but if you give it some thought, it certainly doesn't seem all that hard to believe. For every one player-made pet, how many NPC pets with buffs (and NPCs with buffs, for that matter) do you think exist in the game world? The servers have to manage those, too.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sum total of pets that actually cast self buffs in game. Mage pets (fire only). NPC's cast buffs too, and an NPC pet master will probably buff their pet (maybe. I don't believe mage NPC's burnout their pets, though they may DS them). Therein lies one of the problems, however. As mentioned later in my reply, if resources by NPC's casting are that much of an issue, double (innately) the duration of NPC cast spells (excluding PC pets). NPC's are going to have their buffs on them at any given moment anyways, and if you don't want to make them permiment buffs on the mob, simply double or tripple the time they would normally be on.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The entire act of checking every single NPC and NPC/PC pet that is alive at time X, what buffs they have, what buffs they're missing, what class they are (and thus what buffs they have access to cast), and whether they should refresh any buffs probably is rather resource intensive. If they made this check every second of every minute... well, you can probably see how resources can start to add up. Logically, you space these checks out to balance the load.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is a bad way to program. Checking information, buff tables, all the time. It's FAR FAR better to do an 'event based' system. Buff wears off, a trigger on the NPC goes &quot;wait, buff just wore off, let me refresh it&quot;, and it does so. It doesn't have to check constantly, it gets triggered by the buff wearing off. And if the pet/NPC is busy (fighting), it delays that 'event' until a later time. There are no checks and no 'lag' because of it. The NPC's know better than we do what buffs need to be maintained. <p><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=52886">Rhasin Firestorm</A><BR>
Conjurer of the 59th Season<BR>
Prexus</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/usambus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sambus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 75<br> <font color=#333333>(7/16/02 5:12:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=571.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.shiftclick.net/eq/sigs/60x60tinker.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_mad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Pet Complaints!!! &gt;:-\</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Sum total of pets that actually cast self buffs in game. Mage pets (fire only).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
